# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: birgit-bonnier
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:birgit-bonnier/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:birgit-bonnier/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:birgit-bonnier/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:birgit-bonnier/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:birgit-bonnier/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:birgit-bonnier/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:birgit-bonnier/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Albert Bonnier was the son of Gerhard Bonnier, a Jewish merchant and his wife Ester (née Elkan).
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Gerhard Bonnier was born in Dresden in 1778 as Gutkind Hirschel and later emigrated to Copenhagen.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] There he changed his name to Bonnier and founded a publishing house.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Bonnier's older brother Adolf was from 1827 in Gothenburg as a bookseller and moved two years later to Stockholm.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Albert followed him and worked from 1839 to 1865 with his brother.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] In addition, he founded in 1837 a Förlagsbyrå, from 1858 as Albert Bonniers Förlag AB firmierte.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] The publishing house is today part of the resulting media Bonnier Group AB.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] For training purposes, he traveled from 1840 to two years to Leipzig, Vienna and Pest.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Albert Bonnier was married since 1854 with Betty Rubenson.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Her son Karl Otto was also publisher and led from 1914 the father's company.
[src:birgit-bonnier/albert-bonnier] Bonnier edited and published the *Stockholms Figaro* between 1844 and 1847 and *Sveriges Handelskalendar*, which began in 1859.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:birgit-bonnier/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:birgit-bonnier/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:birgit-bonnier/birgit-bonnier] '**Birgit Bonnier'** is a modern cultivar of domesticated apple which have some resistance to apple scab and mildew.
[src:birgit-bonnier/birgit-bonnier] 'Birgit Bonnier' was developed in Sweden through a cross between the popular 'Cortland' and the 'Lord Lambourne'.
[src:birgit-bonnier/birgit-bonnier] The result is an apple of a pleasant flavor.
[src:birgit-bonnier/birgit-bonnier] Background color is whitish green and flushed or with striped with orange red.
[src:birgit-bonnier/birgit-bonnier] Fruit is low in juiciness making it more recommended for a dessert apple.
[src:birgit-bonnier/birgit-bonnier] This cultivar was named by the Swedish publisher Albert Bonnier, who named it after his wife Birgit.
